Q8: I would draw a circle circumscribed inside a square to indicate the "outside" gender (male) and the biological sex (female) and would write under it what surgeries/therapies
Q37: I would draw a diamond with 46, XX under it and write what surgeries/therapies if any

Q8: I would likely ask the patient what their preference is, but I would generally draw as a square and write in XX or FTM
Q37: I would ask the patient their preference in this situation, but if they did not have a preference, I would draw a diamond with XX underneath it.

Q8: I have drawn the individual using an overlaying circle and square, and then writing their karyotype underneath. It's probably not right, but what I came up with.
Q37: Same as above.

Q8: square w/circle inside - indicate genetic sex but acknowledge indenity
Q37: diamond with circle inside to indicate genetic sex but does not identify with one particular gender

Q8: I would draw the individual as a square with a circle inside.  The circle inside to represent their sex at birth and square to represent their personal gender identity.
Q37: I would probably draw a diamond as this is gender neutral and label XX underneath the symbol to indicate genetic sex.

Q8: Square with note underneath denoting trans man and the patient's preferred pronouns. I've seen a lot of conversation on the Cancer SIG about noting biological sex (46,XX) on the pedigree or placing shapes inside of shapes, but these methods could still lead to confusion (i.e. if karyotype is not truly known or different people interpret shapes inside of shapes differently). I would love to see more standardization of pedigree nomenclature, but until then I would likely use the shape of the patient's gender identity with further description below the shape as appropriate (i.e. trans man, preferred pronouns, etc)
Q37: Diamond with note underneath stating genderqueer and 46,XX. Again, I would chose for my pedigree symbol to reflect the patient's gender identity as accurately as possibly, and I would use a diamond for a patient with a nonbinary gender identity. I'd denote genderqueer and the karyotype underneath the shape just like I would any other medical information that might be relevant to the case.

Q8: I would draw the symbol as a square while I am seeing the patient, to avoid offending him. However, after the session, I would include a circle inside of the square, which is what NCCN has recently proposed as the correct symbol. I like to avoid putting "XX" or "XY" because, as most individuals are born with this configuration of chromosomes, this may not be genetically confirmed. This says to me that this person has had a karyotype, and it is know that they are XX or XY, which for most patients is not the case.
Q37: I would use the diamond symbol to reflect gender fluidity, and put a circle inside, as this individual was born female.

Q8: Square with a circle inside. It is addressed in NCCN guidelines and shows that the male gender is the individual's identity, but that they are biologically female.
Q37: Possibly a diamond with a circle drawn inside and XX written underneath, as they do not identify as one specific gender but are biologically female.

Q8: I would ask what their preferred identity is.  The pedigree is a tool though, it doesn't change anything about who they are.  If we draw a circle, square, octagon, etc.  It doesn't define a person.  It is just an arbitrary way to assess risk.
Q37: Ask if they have a preferred gender.  If not, I would use XX but make a distinction in my notes.  It isn't that complicated.  If we are judging identity by a circle or square, we have bigger problems to work through.

Q8: square with explanation such as FTM or 46XX trans, need to respect patient, but also understand gender-specific risks
Q37: if no defined binary gender expression, would use a diamond with 46XX and explanation by symbol, for same reasons as described above

Q8: There is no standardized pedigree symbol for trans individuals at this point in time.  I have seen this discussed in numerous webinars, lectures, etc., and every clinic seems to have their own take on it.  At my office, we have decided that it would be appropriate to represent a trans man as a square with a circle inside of it (the individual's biological sex is female, but he outwardly identifies as being male).
Q37: I would represent this individuals with a circle on the pedigree, representing the patient's biological sex.  I would make sure, though, to ask the patient which pronoun is preferred and make a note of their preference on the pedigree.

Q8: I would draw a square with "MTF" under it. This accurately shows how he identifies, but also gives the correct medical information.
Q37: I would draw a diamond, notating the chromosomal sex underneath. This way, medical information is conveyed in a way that does not offend the patient.

Q8: Female (circle) on pedigree, with note on side saying that patient identifies as male. My feeling is that the pedigree should show biological sex as it would show up on a karyotype so that inheritance patterns can be properly identified. Cultural or personal identification should of course be noted and respected, but it doesn't override biological sex on a pedigree, especially since the pedigree is for internal use and not seen by the patient.
Q37: Female (circle) on pedigree, with note on side saying that patient identifies as genderqueer. As stated above, I feel that the pedigree should show biological sex as it would show up on a karyotype so that inheritance patterns can be properly identified. Cultural or personal identification should of course be noted and respected, but it doesn't override biological sex on a pedigree, especially since the pedigree is for internal use and not seen by the patient.

Q8: square with a circle inside, shows person is born a woman but identifies as a man
Q37: I don't know technically, but might draw a diamond (which I use for unknown gender) with a circle inside to show born a woman but does not identify with male or female.

Q8: Square around a circle, indicating assumed female sex chromosomes, identifying male
Q37: Diamond with XX underneath

Q8: Assuming patient has disclosed their identification as a trans man, I would draw a square symbol with a circle inside. I would not mark anything related to chromosomes (like drawing a square but writing 46,XX) unless cytogenetic testing has been done.  I also try to take into account patient preferences for how they are represented, by explaining why I have drawn the symbol as I did.  In one situation, the patient was uncomfortable with this, so I represented them as a diamond and wrote a description that was both revealing of medical information and acceptable to the patient.  I believe it was to the effect of "man with ovaries and excess breast tissue."
Q37: I admit that I do not ask all patients how they identify, so it may be dictated by how they are represented in the medical record.  If they are listed as female and their gender expression appears female, I may simple mark them with a circle without further exploration.  If they are listed as female in the medical record but express a genderqueer identity or I perceived that their gender expression is discordant with what is in the medical record, I would draw a diamond with a circle inside and the notation 46,XX. The diamond would represent that the individual has disclosed that they are genderqueer, while the inner circle would represent the chromosomal status and alert me and other viewers of the pedigree that there may be internal organs (e.g. ovaries) that are relevant to the medical inquiry.

Q8: I would draw this individual with a circle to indicate their sex, because this determines what appropriate counseling may be in terms of topics such as breast and ovarian-related counseling. It would be important to specify that they identify as a trans man on the pedigree, however, as well as whether or not the individual has pursued any gender affirming measures such as surgery and hormone therapy that may alter sex-based risks. I would not draw them as the shape that correlates with their gender identity because I believe this could be harmful in that if follow up counseling was provided by someone unaware of the patient's journey, who only glanced at the pedigree, they could improperly define risk for the patient based on their shape on the pedigree being discordant with sex.
Q37: The same as stated above. I think there could be argument for using a diamond to draw attention to the fact that their gender identity is different from their sex, and then indicating the details relating to gender affirming measures next to it. Perhaps this could be done for any individual who identifies as something other than their sex assigned at birth out of respect or recognition for their choice, however, I would stand by not drawing a trans man the same way that I would draw a cis man.
